The anisotropic linear optical response in gerstleyite flake is recorded using polarization-resolved optical absorption spectroscopy. Initially, the optical absorption spectrum from bare glass substrate is characterized to elucidate the substrate effect on the measurement. The optical absorption spectra from the 472Â nm-thick flake are probed in the visible range from 420 to 800Â nm. FigureÂ 4a,b show the optical transmission microscope image and the corresponding AFM image of the flake. The measured reflectance (R), transmittance (T) and absorbance (Aâ=â1âââRâââT) spectra are plotted in Fig.Â 4c. It is observed that the transmittance is much higher than the reflectance. Both the transmittance and reflectance show sharp decline before the wavelength around 450Â nm and then show gradual increase up to 510Â nm. The opposite oscillations in the transmittance and reflectance spectra around the wavelength of 620Â nm is attributed to the thin film interference of light within the flake. However, these oscillations are almost canceled out in the absorbance spectrum. It can be observed that the initial decline in transmittance and reflectance leads to the maximum absorbance before 510Â nm. Afterwards the absorbance rapidly declines up to 570Â nm followed by a gradual decrease continuing till 800Â nm. To obtain further insight about the anisotropic feature of gerstleyite crystal, the polarization-resolved absorbance spectra are systematically recorded for the incident linear polarization angle from 0Â° to 180Â° as shown in Fig.Â 4d, where the linear polarization angle is measured relative to the crystalâs a-axis (x-axis as depicted in Fig.Â 4a). The absorbance spectra show the significant dependence on the incident linear polarization. Interestingly, all the absorbance spectra from 0Â° to 180Â° converge around 650Â nm and a clear crossover around this wavelength can be observed. Further, the polar plots of absorbance at three different wavelengths of 500, 550 and 700Â nm are shown in Fig.Â 4eâg. It is found that the absorbance maxima at 500 and 550Â nm in Fig.Â 4e,f are aligned in 0Â° and 180Â° along the a-axis (x-axis), which are consistent with the observed Raman Ag modes at 432 and 497Â cmâ1 (Fig.Â 3k,l). Whereas the absorbance maxima at 700Â nm in Fig.Â 4g is observed to be 90Â° rotated along the c*-axis (y-axis), which follows the orientations of the Raman Ag modes at 303 and 356Â cmâ1 (Fig.Â 3h,j). Such observation infers that the optical axis of gerstleyite crystal is along the a-axis and c*-axis. The measured absorbance values marked in black squares show two-lobe patterns and can be theoretically fitted as brown solid lines using a sinusoidal function expressed as AÎ¸=Axcos2Î¸+Aysin2Î¸\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
